</div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
<p>The placebo effect occurs more strongly with peripheral aspects of disease processes (such as hypertension, asthma, prostatic hyperplasia, anal fissure, bronchitis) rather than processes that reflect physical disease (such as venous leg ulcers, Crohn’s disease, urinary tract infection, and chronic heart failure.<sup id="cite_ref-171" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-171" title=""><span>[</span>172<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Dylan_Evans" title="Dylan Evans">Dylan Evans</a> has suggested placebos work most strongly upon conditions such as pain, swelling, stomach ulcers, depression, and anxiety that have been linked with activation of the <a href="/wiki/Acute-phase_reaction" title="Acute-phase reaction" class="mw-redirect">acute-phase response</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Evans_172-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Evans-172" title=""><span>[</span>173<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p><a name="List_of_nonmedical_changes" id="List_of_nonmedical_changes"></a></p>
